  "prompt": "What is the value of sec^-1 (cos (-3/5))?",
  "response": "To evaluate \\(\\sec^{-1} (\\cos (-\\frac{3}{5}))\\), let's break down the problem step-by-step.\n\n1. Firstly, compute \\(\\cos(-\\frac{3}{5})\\). Using the property that \\(\\cos(-x) = \\cos(x)\\), we get:\n   \\[\n   \\cos(-\\frac{3}{5}) = \\cos(\\frac{3}{5}).\n   \\]\n\n2. Now, let \\( \\theta = \\frac{3}{5} \\). Then, \\(\\cos(\\theta) = \\cos(\\frac{3}{5})\\).\n\n3. We need to find the value of \\(\\sec^{-1} (\\cos(\\frac{3}{5}))\\):\n   \\[\n   \\sec^{-1} (\\cos(\\theta)).\n   \\]\n\n4. Recall that \\(\\sec(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{\\cos(\\theta)}\\). For \\(\\sec^{-1} (\\cos(\\theta))\\), we're essentially looking for an angle whose secant (reciprocal of the cosine) equals the value \\(\\cos(\\theta)\\).\n\nFor the value of \\(\\cos(\\theta)\\) where \\(\\theta = \\frac{3}{5}\\), we note that \\(\\sec^{-1} x\\) returns an angle \\(\\phi\\) whose secant is \\(x\\).\n\nHowever, \\(\\sec^{-1} (\\cos(\\theta))\\) can be broadly thought of in terms of function inverses and identity. Generally, \\(\\sec^{-1} (x)\\) is defined for \\(|x| \\geq 1\\), and \\(\\cos(\\theta)\\) where \\(\\theta = \\frac{3}{5}\\) does not fall in the range for which \\( \\sec^{-1} \\) is normally defined because \\(\\cos(\\theta)\\) falls between -1 and 1.\n\nDue to the constraints and properties of the inverse secant function, the answer lies in understanding that:\n\n\\[\n\\sec^{-1} (\\cos(\\theta)) \\quad \\text{does not normally yield valid numeric output like elementary trigonometric functions}.\n\\]\n\nThus, strictly mathematically:\n\\[\n\\sec^{-1} (\\cos(\\frac{3}{5})) \\quad \\text{would not return a valid real angle unless context justifies domain restrictions and custom conditions}.\n\\]\n\nThis concludes that \\(\\theta = \\frac{3}{5}\\) where domain-specific constraints make the primary evaluation non-standard.",
